{"add":{"doc":{"id":"082ee98ca1b5528c05f82579ac41cf9fccfcf2a775b66f3573c04da3636d9bd8","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Brown_bear_%28Ursus_arctos_arctos%29_running.jpg/220px-Brown_bear_%28Ursus_arctos_arctos%29_running.jpg","previous":["Owing to its distance from open sea and position on the Southeastern portion of the European continent, Romania has a climate that is temperate and continental, with four distinct seasons. The average annual temperature is 11 °C (52 °F) in the south and 8 °C (46 °F) in the north.[133] In summer, average maximum temperatures in Bucharest rise to 28 °C (82 °F), and temperatures over 35 °C (95 °F) are fairly common in the lower-lying areas of the country.[134] In winter, the average maximum temperature is below 2 °C (36 °F).[134] Precipitation is average, with over 750 mm (30 in) per year only on the highest western mountains, while around Bucharest it drops to around 600 mm (24 in).[135]"],"after":["A high percentage (47% of the land area) of the country is covered with natural and semi-natural ecosystems.[137] Romania has one of the largest areas of undisturbed forest in Europe covering almost 27% of the territory.[138] The fauna consists of 33,792 species of animals, 33,085 invertebrate and 707 vertebrate,[139] with almost 400 unique species of mammals, birds, reptiles and amphibians,[140] including about 50% of Europe's (excluding Russia) brown bears [136] and 20% of its wolves.[141] Some 3,700 plant species have been identified in the country, from which to date 23 have been declared natural monuments, 74 missing, 39 endangered, 171 vulnerable and 1,253 rare.[139] There are almost 10,000 km2 (3,900 sq mi) (about 5% of the total area) of protected areas in Romania covering 13 national parks and three biosphere reserves.[142] The Danube Delta, at 5,800 km2 (2,200 sq mi),[143] is the largest continuous marshland in Europe,[144] and supports 1,688 different plant species alone.[145]"]}}}